         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the Divine Spirits. To Caelemontanus, slave of Caesar, who lived for
               twenty-five years. Aurelia Auxesis made (this) for (her) dearest husband,
               well-deserving.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>There are several indications that this epitaph is modern. Note the
               perfectly round interpuncts throughout, the capital “U” in line 3, and the “G” with a
               rounded bottom in line 6. The letters have fixed-width spacing and seem to be
               impressed or stamped rather than carved. “Caelemontanus" is not elsewhere attested as a slave name but is recorded as a toponym twice in Rome, once in an epitaph (CIL 6.9475) of a hymnologos "de campo Caelemontano" (probably identical with the campus Martialis on the Caelian hill: see C. Buzzetti in LTUR I A-C s.v. "Campus Caelemontanus" 218), once in an inscription recording the restoration by the emperor Septimius Severus of multiple "arcus Caelemontanos" in late 200 or 201 CE (CIL 6.1259 = ILS 424 = EDR127784) The arcus Celemontani are probably identical with the arcus Neroniani that carried part of the aqua Claudia across the Caelian hill (see Z. Mari in LTUR I A-C s.v. "arcus Neroniani" 100-101). It
               is possible that whoever made this modern concoction had seen CIL 6.15236 (= EDR130368), now in the Naples Archaeological Museum, which is
               dedicated by an Aurelia Auxesis to an imperial freedman (not slave) identified as her "coniunx".  (Jennifer Blackwell, John Bodel)</p>
         </div>
